{:proof/problem-id "apm-a94A01", :proof/classification :partial, :proof/output "\n\n---\n\nTARGET SANITY CHECK — mentions-problem-objects? ✅ (characteristic functions, measurable sets, integrals, and \\(L^p\\) norms all appear) · avoids-assuming-conclusion? ✅ (the Lean target only concludes that the limit is an indicator and the \\(L^p\\) criterion after the hypotheses) · meaningful-without-prose? ✅ (the statement about limits of indicators and the symmetric-difference condition is a stand-alone measure-theoretic result) · notes: This target bundles parts (a), (b), and the \\(L^p\\) criterion into one theorem, with the symmetric-difference lemma called out separately.\n\n```\nPROOF-PLAN.EDN\n{:goal \"Identify the limit of characteristic functions and describe when χ_{E_n} → χ_E in L^p.\"\n :terms [{:name \"pointwise limit of indicators\"\n          :meaning \"Since each f_n takes values in {0,1}, any pointwise limit belongs to {0,1}.\"\n          :needed-because \"Allows us to define the limiting set E = {x : f(x)=1}.\"}\n         {:name \"dominated convergence theorem\"\n          :meaning \"Bounded convergence (|f_n g| ≤ |g|) gives limit of integrals.\"\n          :needed-because \"Yields part (b).\"}\n         {:name \"symmetric difference\"\n          :meaning \"‖χ_{E_n}-χ_E‖_p^p = μ(E_n Δ E).\"\n          :needed-because \"Translates L^p convergence into measure conditions.\"}]\n :strategy [{:id :s1\n             :formal-dependency \"Pointwise limits of {0,1}-valued functions\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 definition of E\"\n             :why-this-now \"Show f equals χ_E almost everywhere.\"\n             :lean-target \"limit_indicator_is_indicator\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Mathlib already has measurability of indicator functions; need a lemma about eventual constant values.\"}\n            {:id :s2\n             :formal-dependency \"Dominated convergence theorem\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 identification of f\"\n             :why-this-now \"Derive convergence of integrals for every integrable g.\"\n             :lean-target \"indicator_integral_limit\"\n             :mathlib-status \"DomConv exists; straightforward after measurability.\"}\n            {:id :s3\n             :formal-dependency \"Symmetric-difference measure formula\"\n             :informal-dependency \"Stage 1 expression for f\"\n             :why-this-now \"Provide necessary/sufficient condition for L^p convergence.\"\n             :lean-target \"indicator_Lp_convergence\"\n             :mathlib-status \"Need lemma ‖χ_A - χ_B‖_p^p = μ(A Δ B).\"}]\n :stage-status {:stage1 :done :stage2 :done :stage3 :in-progress :stage4 :pending}}\n```\n\n```\nFORMAL-ALIGNMENT.EDN\n{:main-claim {:informal-claim \"Pointwise limits of characteristic functions stay characteristic, integrals converge by dominated convergence, and L^p convergence occurs exactly when the symmetric-difference measure tends to zero.\"\n             :formal-name \"indicator_limit_integral_Lp\"\n             :formal-target \"∀ (E_n : ℕ → Set ℝ), (∀ n, MeasurableSet (E_n n)) → (∀ᵐ x, Tendsto (fun n => (E_n n).indicator (1 : ℝ) x) atTop (𝓝 (E.indicator (1 : ℝ) x))) → (∀ᵐ x, (E.indicator (1 : ℝ) x) ∈ {0,1}) ∧ (∀ g ∈ L1, ∫ g • χ_{E_n} → ∫ g • χ_E) ∧ (∀ p ∈ [1,∞), ‖χ_{E_n}-χ_E‖_{L^p} → 0 ↔ μ(E_n Δ E) → 0)\"\n             :sanity-check {:mentions-problem-objects? true\n                            :avoids-assuming-conclusion? true\n                            :meaningful-without-prose? true\n                            :notes \"Bundles parts (a), (b), and the L^p criterion into one Lean target.\"}}\n :alignments [{:formal-name \"indicator_limit_integral_Lp\"\n              :formal-statement \"(see formal-target)\"\n              :informal-clause \"Full theorem (a)+(b)+Lp statement.\"\n              :role :main-theorem}\n             {:formal-name \"indicator_Lp_distance\"\n              :formal-statement \"‖Set.indicator ℝ (μ:=μ) E - Set.indicator ℝ (μ:=μ) F‖_{L^p(μ)}^p = μ(E Δ F)\"\n              :informal-clause \"Justifies the L^p iff symmetric difference condition.\"\n              :role :helper-lemma}]}\n```\n\n---\n\n**Why it’s hard.** Pointwise limits of characteristic functions need not converge everywhere, so you must juggle “almost everywhere” limitations and prove the limit still only takes the values \\(0\\) or \\(1\\). For part (b) the trap is forgetting to justify interchange of limit and integral: the indicators are only bounded—not dominated by an integrable constant—so you must dominate \\(g \\chi_{E_n}\\) by \\(|g|\\). Finally, many people assert \\(L^p\\) convergence “obviously” holds without computing the norm; the necessary-and-sufficient condition is exactly the measure of the symmetric difference tending to zero.\n\n**Key insight.** Define \\(E = \\{x : f(x)=1\\}\\). Because each \\(f_n\\) takes values in \\(\\{0,1\\}\\), the pointwise limit \\(f\\) also lies in \\(\\{0,1\\}\\), so \\(f = \\chi_E\\) almost everywhere and \\(E\\) is measurable. Then dominated convergence with dominating function \\(|g|\\) proves \\(\\int g \\chi_{E_n} \\to \\int g \\chi_E\\). The \\(L^p\\)-criterion follows from \\(\\|\\chi_{E_n}-\\chi_E\\|_p^p = \\mu(E_n \\,\\triangle\\, E)\\), so \\(L^p\\)-convergence is equivalent to the symmetric-difference measure going to zero.\n\n**Complete proof.**\n1. Since every \\(f_n\\) is measurable and \\(\\{0,1\\}\\)-valued, the a.e. limit \\(f\\) is measurable and \\(\\{0,1\\}\\)-valued; letting \\(E=f^{-1}(\\{1\\})\\) gives \\(f=\\chi_E\\) almost everywhere.\n2. For any \\(g\\in L^1(\\mathbb R)\\), \\(|g\\chi_{E_n}| \\le |g|\\), so dominated convergence yields \\(\\int g\\chi_{E_n} \\to \\int g\\chi_E\\), i.e. \\(\\int_{E_n} g \\to \\int_E g\\).\n3. Because \\(|\\chi_{E_n}-\\chi_E|^p = |\\chi_{E_n}-\\chi_E|\\), we have \\(\\|\\chi_{E_n}-\\chi_E\\|_p^p = \\mu(E_n\\triangle E)\\). Hence \\(\\chi_{E_n}\\to\\chi_E\\) in \\(L^p\\) iff \\(\\mu(E_n\\triangle E)\\to 0\\).\n\n**Lean 4 formalization.**  \n- Main target (`formal-alignment.edn`): `indicator_limit_integral_Lp`, bundling parts (a), (b), and the \\(L^p\\) criterion.  \n- Plan (`proof-plan.edn`):  \n  1. `limit_indicator_is_indicator`: prove the a.e. pointwise limit is an indicator of some measurable \\(E\\).  \n  2. `indicator_integral_limit`: apply `tendsto_integral_of_dominated_convergence` with dominator \\(|g|\\).  \n  3. `indicator_Lp_convergence`: show \\(\\|\\chi_A-\\chi_B\\|_p^p = \\mu(A\\triangle B)\\).  \n- Stage 3 is still in progress: these lemmas need to be encoded in `Main.lean`; no `sorry`s have been inserted yet. The remaining work is largely wiring existing Mathlib results (AE convergence, DCT, symmetric-difference lemmas) together.\n\n**What connects.** The symmetric-difference computation is the standard tool for metrizing convergence in measure, so the same reasoning reappears in real-analysis courses and probability when discussing convergence of events. Dominated convergence for sequences of indicators times arbitrary \\(L^1\\) functions is a stock move for exchanging limits and integrals in measure theory.\n\nArtifacts updated: `execute.md` now contains detailed Stage 1–4 write-ups, `proof-plan.edn` and `formal-alignment.edn` describe the formal targets, and `changelog.edn` logs workspace init plus Stage 1/2 completion and Stage 3’s in-progress status.", :proof/extraction {:phases {}, :dependency-graph nil, :arse-questions nil, :classification :partial, :phase-count 0, :dep-graph-count 0, :arse-count 0}, :proof/frame-workspace {:frame/lean-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Frames/A94A01/Apm_v2_a94A01_1775002871618", :frame/id "apm-v2-a94A01-1775002871618", :workspace/owner-repo "futon6", :workspace/generated-at "2026-04-01T00:21:11.641463Z", :frame/shared-extension-root "/home/joe/code/apm-lean/ApmCanaries/Local", :frame/module-root "ApmCanaries.Frames.A94A01.Apm_v2_a94A01_1775002871618", :proof/problem-id "a94A01", :workspace/schema "proof-frame-workspace.v1", :